This paper focuses on training an agent to play a complex sequential social dilemma game, which falls under the category of multi-agent reinforcement learning. Therefore, cs.MA is a likely sub-category. The paper also uses neural network-based policy models, which suggests that cs.AI and cs.LG are also likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of supervised learning and reinforcement learning, which are sub-fields of machine learning, further supporting cs.AI and cs.LG. The paper also mentions the use of natural language processing techniques to extract information from game logs, which suggests that cs.CL is a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses game theory and the concept of non-cooperative games, which suggests that cs.GT is a possible sub-category.
